article.headline: Hardrick hits layup with .9 to play
article.linkText: Lady Bulldogs upset No. 1 Lady Vols in OT
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Georgia's Janese Hardrick was determined
to make the last-second layup this time to beat Tennessee.

She did, and No. 20 Georgia stunned the top-ranked Lady Vols
68-66 in overtime Saturday night to advance to the Southeastern
Conference tournament championship game.

Hardrick, a freshman, missed a layup in the final seconds in the
Lady Bulldogs' 70-67 home loss to Tennessee on Feb. 12.

"That's exactly what was going through my mind," Hardrick
said. "I just tried to focus on my layup, because I know the last
game I missed the layup that would have won us the game. This time
it went down."

With the score tied at 66 with 21 seconds left, Hardrick got the
ball, dribbled around and then drove to the basket to score the
winner with .9 on the clock.

The Lady Vols (26-3) pushed the lead to four in overtime and
never trailed in the extra period until Alexis Kendrick hit a
3-pointer with 45 seconds left, putting Georgia ahead 66-63.

Tennessee responded with a 3-pointer by Brittany Jackson, but it
wasn't enough.

"We're disappointed in the outcome of the game, especially
after we went up four, but we didn't make the defensive stops,"
Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said.

Kendrick finished with 16 points. Ebony Felder and Christi
Thomas had 12 apiece and Cori Chambers 10 for Georgia (22-8).
Thomas also had 11 rebounds.

Shyra Ely led Tennessee with 27 points and 12 rebounds, and
Tasha Butts added 17 points.

Hardrick, who had to leave the game after falling hard when she
ran into a screen, returned to take a charge and finished with nine
points.

She said she hurt her right ribs, but would be fine for Sunday's
championship game against No. 21 Vanderbilt, a 78-66 winner over
No. 15 LSU in the second semifinal.

"I thought both teams defended each other well and made each
other make plays, which is what happens this time of year when
teams are so familiar with each other," Georgia coach Andy Landers
said. "A great game broke out and we're really pleased that we won
it."

Georgia is back in the title game for the first time since 2001,
when the Bulldogs won their fourth tournament crown. Georgia is
trying to become the second team to take the tournament by winning
four games. Auburn did it in 1997.

Tennessee did everything it could, but the Lady Vols could never
pull far enough away. Tennessee, which won its seventh straight SEC
regular-season title after going 14-0 in league play, failed to
reach the championship game for the third time in the last four
years.

Summitt said she still believes the Lady Vols deserve a No. 1
seed in the NCAA tournament despite Saturday's loss.

"No one in America plays this schedule," Summitt said. "If
this costs us, then I'll have to rethink our regular season
(schedule). I'll play a patsy schedule like some of these other
teams."

The Lady Bulldogs were ahead by five with 8:11 left when
Tennessee tied it at 50 after Ely had a basket and three-point
play.

Georgia scored the next five points to go ahead again with 1:56
remaining.

Ely scored and Butts made the first of two free throws to cut it
to 55-53 and set up a frenetic ending.

Ely hit a baseline jumper to tie it at 55, and Kendrick made a
difficult jumper at the other end to put Georgia ahead with 6.1
seconds to go.

Butts forced overtime when she made a leaner in the lane with
six-tenths of a second left.

Butts made six straight free throws to score all of Tennessee's
points in overtime until Jackson's 3. Butts' last pair of free
throws put the Lady Vols ahead 63-59 with 1:57 left in overtime.
But at the other end, she fouled Felder, who sank both free throws.

Then Sherill Baker stole the ball from Butts on the inbounds
pass, turned around and tossed it into the basket to tie it at 63,
setting up the exciting ending.
